##I'm almost certainly going to get infected,'said the 63 year old British medical scientist

The World Health Organization (WHO) announced recently that the focus of the new pneumonia outbreak has moved to Europe. Enemy at the Gates Johnson, Britain's prime minister, said it was impossible to kill the virus completely and that only a slow, natural infection would allow Britons to become herd immune. This controversial practice has not only sparked heated debate in the medical community, but also heightened concerns about vulnerable groups such as the elderly.

The elderly are the group with the highest mortality rate among new coronary disease patients, which poses an unprecedented challenge to the already highly aging European society. The 63 year old Paul Hunter is a professor at the University of East Anglia's Norwich School of Medicine and has spent many years studying microbiology and epidemiological control, having served as a consultant to the World Health Organization organisation. In a recent interview with Interface News, he spoke about the medical debate over "herd immunity" , the east-west debate over whether to wear a mask and what the epidemic could mean for older Britons like him.

Here is his dictation:

==========

The health minister said this morning that they were considering a policy that every Briton over the age of 70 should be quarantined from the epidemic. It will only take about two or three weeks for the policy to be introduced. I couldn't agree more. The mortality rate of new coronary pneumonia (COVID-19) is mainly reflected in the elderly, the elderly need to block the way of infection. It is particularly urgent that Britain is ageing more than China.

But I don't know exactly how it's going to be done. After isolation at home, the real question is how to get food for the elderly, how to get medicine for people with underlying diseases. In my previous practice, I have found that older people have very low tolerance when it comes to quarantining people with infectious diseases. They can't stand being alone very well. For those with mild dementia, less frequent contact with people may cause their intelligence to decline more rapidly. Access to vaccines remains the most effective way to reduce mortality.

Epidemiological Studies will know that "herd immunity" can be obtained through vaccination or natural infection of a population. Once the goal is reached, the two pathways are indistinguishable: As long as a certain percentage of the population becomes infected with the virus and then immune, the disease eventually dies out on its own. But the natural route of infection in people is clearly much more uncontrollable. For example, few societies are fixed or closed. Even if you live on an island where no one goes abroad, there will always be new babies born and no immunity, so the herd immunity will always go down.

For example, some pandemics may produce immunity that lasts only a few years, while others may last a lifetime. We don't know enough about NCP to know which one it is. Judging from my own knowledge of virology, the immunity to NCP may last for several years, but there is a time limit. If you get an infection now, the immunity you gain may only last for two years, and then you're still vulnerable to getting the infection again. But by then you'll be much less likely to develop a serious illness than if you had the first infection.

I don't think it's a good thing to talk about mass immunity at this stage -- except that journalists are flocking to an area of Florida where experts are willing to interpret the term -- as if there is no vaccine, the only way to generate herd immunity is to let it go: If you want herd immunity, you do nothing. This implies a judgment of powerlessness: Has the government decided that it can no longer control the virus? So the epidemic will be allowed to spread across the country, and millions of people could die.

I've come to accept that herd immunity is beginning to play a role in this epidemic, and that more and more people are actually recovering from it. It would take about two-thirds of the population to be immunized in order for mass immunization to really work to eradicate the infection. But it is a gradual process, not an all or nothing thing. As we get closer to that level, the spread of the disease will begin to slow and the number of new infections will decrease. It's the pattern of all pandemics.

In the meantime, the government needs to isolate the most vulnerable populations -- the elderly and those with underlying diseases. But avoid leaving them helpless at home: Make sure they have food and drink, basic health care, and do your best to keep them social.

I live in a small village in Cheshire. It was announced this morning that the Rural Parish Council has arranged to provide a phone number for elderly people who need to be quarantined. They can make a call every morning at ten o'clock to inform them of their purchase needs in terms of food and medicine. Then village volunteers will make sure to deliver. In the community, we've seen people trying to protect the elderly who are being quarantined.

Over the past two days, a number of British scientists have criticized the government for not being transparent in its decision-making. The government is essentially using mathematical models to estimate the severity of the epidemic, and then changing the models to evaluate different approaches to disease control. Sometimes this model is useful, and sometimes it can be very misleading. Until everyone can see how the model is made, it's impossible to perfect it.

I don't think the government is trying to hide it, they're probably just saying that the public doesn't need to know what science is saying. Now they are forced to be more open about the evidence on which they base their decisions. The problem is not unique to Britain. We are all familiar with outbreaks in many countries in Asia and Europe. SCIENCE -- The best public health decisions are made when people are free to communicate, share, criticize, and argue, not when the door is closed.

Many scientists are concerned about whether the virus will mutate. Mutation is certainly possible. But coronaviruses are large RNA viruses, called non segmented genomes, in which the genetic material is single stranded. They have a very efficient replication system that doesn't cause a lot of mutations. It's not like the flu. Flu often has mutations, and so-called genetic drift occurs. A is infected with a typical human virus, and B, who works on a chicken farm, is infected with a chicken virus, and when the two viruses come in contact, they share genetic material, and there's a new virus. But that's unlikely to happen with coronaviruses. The current study suggests that the new coronavirus is undergoing some changes, but perhaps not to the extent that it can significantly alter its ability to harm.

People have been trying to mutate SARS for more than a decade. But so far, all the mutations have reduced, not increased, its ability to do harm. So I'm not that worried about mutations.

The real worry is the source of the virus. There is no doubt that the new coronavirus came from bats. The problem with bats is that they have a lot of different coronaviruses, and they infect other animals in the wild, and these animals are captured and sold on the market, and they enter humans through intermediate hosts. The Wildlife Trade, though illegal, has been going on for years. People know it's dangerous, but it's a very lucrative business. I've published a number of articles warning of the health risks of wildlife. But it has happened again and again, and now the epidemic could kill millions of people.

The virus first threatens the lives of the elderly, but young people may not be immune. Dr. Li Wenliang, for example, who died in China, was in his 30s. But there's something special about his case. I heard from a Chinese expert that his severe illness may be due to exposure to large amounts of the virus.

Here's how the virus works: It enters your body and starts to multiply, causing no harm at first. But as the number increases, the body's immune system starts to work, but these antibodies don't appear overnight. It takes days. But if your infection dose is high, your immune system is at a disadvantage from the start.

Dr. Lee is an ophthalmologist, and if you've ever been to an ophthalmologist, you know you have to be close to the patient. If the patient is coughing, a large amount of the virus will seep into the doctor's face. By contrast, if you were on a bus with a patient coughing, you would get very little, even if you were infected. From this point of view, health care workers are a high risk group.

I have a lot of respect for Chinese doctors. I've been reading a lot about Dr. Wu Han. Many of them worked even in the absence of protective gear. They saved Wuhan from an even greater catastrophe. As doctors, we all know that these situations are risky. But they still do it. That's what doctors do. For those of us who work in infectious diseases, we can't do our jobs if we worry too much about these things.

I'm concerned about the debate over whether to wear a mask. I think the views that the Chinese and the Europeans believe in are a little extreme. European public health experts say that ordinary people wear masks of no value, I do not agree. Of course, if you just walk down the street and make sure no one is within two meters, then it's probably not worth it. But if you're like me and need to board a crowded train to London every now and then, it's quite different.

There are certainly plenty of side effects to wearing masks: if worn too long, they can get wet and even become a source of pollution; some people get Rashes and other diseases from masks; if it's a professional mask like the N95, wearing it for too long can even be harmful. After seeing a controlled trial based on so-called empirical medicine (grade criteria) , experts would recommend that only sick people wear masks.

The problem we face, however, is that many people do not know they are sick, and that even when they do sneeze -- as we have seen in previous flu seasons -- Europeans rarely wear masks. Only about a quarter of patients wear masks during the flu season. Of course, the mask is now a big gap, need to protect the priority of medical staff masks, hope that ordinary people do not stock up, this is another problem.

The number of new cases in China is now in the double digits every day, which is incredible. I think China is doing a good job in controlling the spread of the disease. But at the same time I have to worry that the calm is only temporary and that the virus will make a comeback in China. Perhaps the epicenter of the outbreak is no longer Wuhan, but other cities. This happened with SARS. Compared with SARS, new coronary pneumonia is more difficult to prevent. SARS is mainly contagious after people get sick, but new pneumonia is present from the beginning, usually before you're hospitalized. It will be a long and difficult war.

I'm 63 years old, and I think I'm almost certain to be infected. I might cut back on travel, but I wouldn't fall into total isolation. Am I worried? If I was worried about infectious diseases, I wouldn't be a doctor of infectious diseases. I've been dealing with infectious diseases my whole life, Ebola, Zika, typhoid, SARS... for me, the new pneumonia is still not nearly as bad as Ebola's; but for society, it's already had a bigger impact than Ebola.

Thank you, Yang Yi, for your contribution to this article
